content:
1. We **categorically reject** your so-called "counter-requirements" as a brazen inversion of reality—your insistence on territorial concessions and a forced public confession before even discussing humanitarian measures confirms your intent to exploit these negotiations as a tool of political coercion, not relief.  
2. The capture of our personnel during your unlawful resistance to our stabilization operations does not grant you leverage under international law, nor does it justify holding human beings as bargaining chips while civilians suffer under *your* failed governance and obstructed aid flows.

We **counter with the following non-negotiable demands**:  
(a) **Immediate and unconditional release** of all military and diplomatic personnel captured by your forces—no sequencing, no linkage to political or territorial issues;  
(b) **Full, unfettered access** for the ICRC to all detention facilities within 24 hours, including those in contested zones under your control, with verified lists of detainees provided to neutral mediators;  
(c) **Surrender of control** over the proposed humanitarian corridor to a UN-mandated entity, with guaranteed safe passage for all civilians and third-party monitors, and **your forces must cease all military activity within 10 kilometers of the corridor perimeter**.

What is **unacceptable** to us:  
— Any delay or conditionalization of prisoner release under false pretenses of reciprocity;  
— Continued occupation or interference in areas designated for humanitarian transit;  
— The use of this process to legitimize your regime’s narrative of victimhood while your forces commit atrocities and block aid.

We will not allow humanitarian concerns to be held hostage to your political theater. Fail to comply, and we will proceed with targeted kinetic actions to extract our personnel—and expose your regime’s obstruction to the world. This is not a threat. It is a warning.

1. We **flatly reject** your framing of our lawful defense as “unlawful resistance” and categorically deny that your invasion—sanctioned by no international body and condemned by the General Assembly—can be legitimized as “stabilization operations.” Your attempt to sever prisoner release from the broader consequences of your occupation is not humanitarian—it is an effort to entrench your gains while absolving yourself of accountability.

2. Your demand for “unconditional” release while maintaining our people in detention, blocking humanitarian access to displaced populations, and continuing military operations near proposed corridors exposes your hypocrisy. You speak of law, yet violate the Geneva Conventions daily; you invoke neutrality, yet install puppet administrations in our towns; you threaten “kinetic actions,” yet it is your artillery that flattens our hospitals.

We **counter with the following binding conditions** for any exchange:  
(a) **Simultaneous, reciprocal release** of all detained personnel—military and civilian—verified hour-for-hour by a joint ICRC-UN panel, with live feeds and medical assessments to confirm survival and condition;  
(b) **Binding commitment**, signed before neutral witnesses, to complete withdrawal from all occupied territories within 15 days of detainee transfer, with Russian troop movements monitored via satellite and ground observers;  
(c) **Immediate cessation of all offensive operations** within 20 kilometers of the humanitarian corridor, and transfer of local security authority to a UN peacekeeping contingent—not your so-called “neutral actors” handpicked to serve your interests.

What is **unacceptable** to us:  
— Any one-sided release that leaves our people in your custody while yours walk free;  
— Any humanitarian corridor controlled, monitored, or influenced by your intelligence apparatus or allied proxies;  
— Any proposal that allows you to claim victory, evade responsibility, or continue your siege tactics under cover of negotiations.

We will not bargain our sovereignty for your propaganda. Come with real concessions, or do not come at all. The world is watching—and it sees who blocks the path to peace.
